table for damage they unlawfully cause. The book offers scholars and policymakers a full analysis of the legal and policy issues under debate, and it brings into sharp focus the impact of preemption on the lives of people involved in actual lawsuits. McGarity highlights the arguments for and against preemption and suggests guidelines for resolving difficult issues in a variety of contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aExclusive and concurrent legislative powersxUnited States. 0aExclusive and concurrent legislative powerszUnited States. 0aFederal governmentxUnited States. 0aFederal governmentzUnited States. 0aJudicial reviewxUnited States. 0aJudicial reviewzUnited States. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerxUnited States. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzUnited States. 7aLAW / Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300152203423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300152203.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles